[
  {
    "text": "WorldLines defines memory-to-plan translation as the concrete algorithmic process it uses to map long-term memory into actionable plans under partial observability, not as a foundational problem in itself.",
    "topic": "Definition of memory-to-plan translation"
  },
  {
    "text": "The foundational problems identified are: (1) partial observability of the current world state, (2) overwritten or lost world state information across time steps, and (3) the need for agents to act correctly over long horizons despite (1) and (2).",
    "topic": "Foundational problems"
  },
  {
    "text": "Memory-to-plan translation is the chosen implementation technique within WorldLines to address these foundational problems, but alternative techniques could exist without changing the underlying problems.",
    "topic": "Implementation vs. problem"
  },
  {
    "text": "The paper does not treat memory-to-plan translation as a necessary challenge for all embodied agents, but as an engineered solution within its specific architecture for handling partial observability and overwritten states.",
    "topic": "Generality of the approach"
  }
]
